{"amendments":[{"body":"src/adapters/fs.rs:2777-2839 and src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:410-445 still treat a runless `record_bead_start` replay as a brand-new attempt once the original row has already been finalized. The finalized-attempt guard only runs when `run_id` is `Some`, and `find_matching_running_task_run` only looks at non-terminal rows. Replaying the original start after a runless completion therefore appends a second `Running` row; after snapshot reconciliation in src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:164-224, the milestone flips back to `Active` even though the bead already finished.","rationale":"I reproduced this with a focused integration test. Start replays are a normal partial-write recovery case, so this corrupts both the lineage audit and the milestone snapshot."},{"body":"src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:462-553 and src/adapters/fs.rs:2892-2907, 3013-3026, 3077-3083, 3134-3135 still implement legacy collapse/backfill behavior for old start/completion row shapes. The bead explicitly says there is no preexisting milestone data and that migration/repair paths should be removed. As written, `update_task_run` and `find_runs_for_bead` silently merge malformed or legacy NDJSON into synthetic attempts instead of rejecting it, so the bead-audit query can return reconstructed history rather than the exact persisted lineage.","rationale":"This is a correctness and auditability problem, not just cleanup: hidden repair makes corrupt lineage harder to detect and directly contradicts the acceptance criteria for this bead."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone model/service/FS adapter changes end-to-end and ran `cargo test milestone_record --quiet` successfully. I found two correctness issues: a reproducible stale runless-start replay that reopens completed beads, and remaining legacy repair paths that violate the no-migration contract and can fabricate audit history."}